Riemannian geometry and Euclidean geometry are both types of geometries that describe the properties of space. Euclidean geometry is a geometry that assumes the space has flat, straight lines and constant angles, which is the geometry we are most familiar with in our everyday experience. Riemannian geometry, on the other hand, is a geometry that allows for curved space.

One of the main differences between Riemannian geometry and Euclidean geometry is that Riemannian geometry allows for curved lines and surfaces, while Euclidean geometry assumes that all lines and surfaces are straight and flat. Riemannian geometry also allows for the curvature of space to change from point to point, whereas Euclidean geometry assumes that space is flat and homogeneous.

Another difference between Riemannian geometry and Euclidean geometry is the way in which they measure distance. In Euclidean geometry, distance is measured by the Pythagorean theorem, which states that the square of the distance between two points is equal to the sum of the squares of the lengths of the two perpendicular lines between them. In Riemannian geometry, distance is measured using a metric, which can take into account the curvature of space.

Riemannian geometry is also more general than Euclidean geometry, as it can describe a wider range of spaces, including curved spaces, spaces with variable curvature, and spaces with non-Euclidean properties.

Overall, Riemannian geometry is a more general and flexible type of geometry that allows for the description of curved, non-Euclidean spaces, while Euclidean geometry is a simpler and more familiar type of geometry that assumes straight, flat lines and surfaces.
